  "prompt": "Can you hard boil eggs in the microwave?",
  "response": "**No, you cannot reliably and safely hard-boil eggs in the microwave.**\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Exploding Eggs:** Microwaves heat food unevenly. The rapid and uneven heating of the water inside the egg can create a build-up of steam pressure, leading to the egg exploding. This is not only messy but also potentially dangerous, as hot egg can splatter.\n*   **Uneven Cooking:** Even if the egg doesn't explode, the uneven heating can result in some parts of the egg being overcooked and rubbery while other parts are still undercooked.\n*   **Texture:** Microwave-cooked eggs often have a rubbery or tough texture.\n\n**Safer Alternatives:**\n\nThe best and safest way to cook hard-boiled eggs is using traditional methods:\n\n1.  **Stovetop:** Place eggs in a saucepan, cover with cold water, bring to a boil, then simmer for 10-15 minutes depending on your desired yolk consistency.\n2.  **Instant Pot:** Cook eggs in the Instant Pot for a set time, followed by a natural or quick pressure release.\n\nIf you want to cook eggs in the microwave, scrambled or poached eggs are a much better alternative and less risky. There are specific microwave egg cookers available for these purposes.\n",
